===Etymology===
{{wikipedia|Britain (name)}}
{{etyl|enm}} {{term|Breteyne|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|Bretaigne|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|Britannia|lang=la}}, earlier ''Brittania'', from ''Brittani'' 'Britons', from British Celtic *''Pritani'' (compare {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|Prydain}} 'Britain'), from a {{proto|Celtic}} *''kʷritanī'', *''kʷritenī'', whence   {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|Prydyn}} 'Picts', {{etyl|sga|-}} ''Cruthne, Cru(i)then-túath'' 'Picts'.

The Middle English term primarily referred to the duchy of [[Brittany]], in later use specified as ''Little Britain'' or ''the less Britain'', etc., imitating Middle Latin ''Britannia minor''.
The application of the name to Great Britain and the British Empire is modern. The legend ''Brittaniarum rex'' "king of the Britains" appears on coins from the reign of George III, beginning in 1816.

